# Full Codebase Analysis — Cross-Platform Portability

After tracing the entire execution pipeline, here is my analysis of whether the framework will work on any new laptop without manual intervention.

## ✅ Will It Automatically Detect the System?

**Yes.** The hardware detection in [profiler.py](file:///e:/Programming/Projects/GPGPU%20PROJECT/ai-workload-benchmarking-framework/app/features/system_profile/profiler.py) covers all platforms:

| Platform     | CPU Detection                     | GPU Detection                           |
|-------------|-----------------------------------|-----------------------------------------|
| **Windows** | `py-cpuinfo` library              | `GPUtil` (NVIDIA) → PowerShell `Get-CimInstance` fallback (Intel/AMD) |
| **Linux**   | `py-cpuinfo` library              | `GPUtil` (NVIDIA) → `lspci` fallback (Intel/AMD) |
| **macOS**   | `py-cpuinfo` + `sysctl` (Apple Silicon) | `system_profiler SPDisplaysDataType` (Apple/Intel/AMD) |

## ✅ Will It Automatically Choose the Right Backend & Device?

**Yes.** The [recommender.py](file:///e:/Programming/Projects/GPGPU%20PROJECT/ai-workload-benchmarking-framework/app/features/system_profile/recommender.py) maps hardware → settings:

| Hardware Detected      | Backend Selected | Device | Reasoning |
|------------------------|-----------------|--------|-----------|
| Intel GPU (Iris Xe, Arc) | OpenVINO | GPU | Best optimization for Intel silicon |
| NVIDIA GPU             | ONNX Runtime    | GPU  | Uses CUDA execution provider |
| AMD GPU                | ONNX Runtime    | GPU  | Uses DirectML/ROCm provider |
| Apple Silicon Mac      | ONNX Runtime    | CPU  | CoreML acceleration under the hood |
| Intel CPU (no GPU)     | OpenVINO        | CPU  | Optimized for Intel instruction sets |
| Other CPU (no GPU)     | ONNX Runtime    | CPU  | Universal fallback |

## ✅ Will It Automatically Pick the Right GenAI Model?

**Yes.** The recommender checks available VRAM/RAM and selects the most powerful model the system can handle:

| Available Memory | Model Selected | Why |
|-----------------|----------------|-----|
| ≥ 8000 MB       | Llama-3-8B (INT4) | Largest, most capable |
| ≥ 4500 MB       | Phi-3-Mini (INT4)  | Mid-tier, strong performance |
| ≥ 2000 MB       | TinyLlama 1.1B (INT4) | Lightweight, safe on low-end systems |
| < 2000 MB       | TinyLlama 1.1B (INT4) | Fallback — smallest available model |

## ✅ Will It Automatically Download the Model?

**Yes.** [model_utils.py](file:///e:/Programming/Projects/GPGPU%20PROJECT/ai-workload-benchmarking-framework/app/features/genai/model_utils.py) checks if the model directory exists. If missing, it calls `huggingface_hub.snapshot_download()` automatically. The UI shows a "Downloading model..." status message during download.

## ⚠️ One Requirement: `pip install`

The user **must run `pip install -r requirements.txt`** on the new laptop first. All needed libraries ([openvino](file:///e:/Programming/Projects/GPGPU%20PROJECT/ai-workload-benchmarking-framework/app/features/system_profile/device_detector.py#10-24), `openvino-genai`, `onnxruntime`, `huggingface_hub`, `psutil`, `py-cpuinfo`, `GPUtil`, `streamlit`) are listed there. After that, `streamlit run app/main.py` handles everything else automatically.

## End-to-End Flow on a New Laptop

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[pip install -r requirements.txt] --> B[streamlit run app/main.py]
    B --> C[profiler.py detects CPU/GPU/OS/RAM]
    C --> D[recommender.py selects Backend + Device + Model]
    D --> E[benchmark_form.py pre-fills UI with recommendations]
    E --> F[User clicks 'Run Benchmark']
    F --> G{Model downloaded locally?}
    G -- Yes --> H[Run benchmark immediately]
    G -- No --> I[Auto-download from HuggingFace]
    I --> H
    H --> J[Display results in dashboard]
```
